SIMPLE: condign
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Condign
<hw>Con*dign"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>condigne</ets>, L. <ets>condignus</ets> very worthy;
<ets>con-</ets> + <ets>dignus</ets> worthy. See <er>Deign</er>, and cf.
<er>Digne</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Worthy; suitable; deserving;
fit.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Condign</qex> and worthy praise.</q>
<rj><qau>Udall.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Herself of all that rule she deemend most <qex>condign</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Deserved; adequate; suitable to the fault or
crime.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Condign</xex> censure.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Milman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Unless it were a bloody murderer . . . ⟦br⟧
I never gave them <qex>condign</qex> punishment.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Condignity</ent>⟦br⟧
